African horse sickness, South Africa
------------------------------------
Information received on 12 Mar 2014 from Dr Bothle Michael Modisane, Chief Director, Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries, Animal Production and Health, Pretoria, South Africa.

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 5 Mar 2014
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 7 Mar 2014
Report date: 11 Mar 2014
Date submitted to OIE: 12 Mar 2014
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 3 Jul 2013
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: African horse sickness virus
Serotype: pending
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks:
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1 (WCP_AHS_2014_001): WCP_AHS_2014_001, Bergriver, Western Cape Province
Date of start of the outbreak: 5 Mar 2014
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Equidae / - / 2 / 0 / 0 / 0

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: vectors
Epidemiological comments: an outbreak was detected within South Africa's African horse sickness protection zone. The protection zone serves to protect South Africa's African horse sickness free zone from the rest of the country where African horse sickness is endemic.

Control measures
Measures applied: movement control inside the country; no vaccination; no treatment of affected animals.
Measures to be applied: vaccination in response to the outbreak(s).

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
University of Pretoria Veterinary Genetics Laboratory (private laboratory) / Equidae / real-time PCR / 7 Mar 2014 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

