Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[African horse sickness (AHS) (peste equina africana, peste equine) is an infectious, non-contagious arthropod borne disease of equidae, caused by a double-stranded RNA _Orbivirus_ belonging to the family _Reoviridae_. 9 antigenically distinct serotypes of AHSV have been identified by virus neutralization.

AHS is enzootic in sub-Saharan Africa, although occasional outbreaks have occurred in northern Africa (1965, 1989-1990), the Middle East (1959-1961), and in Europe (Spain, 1966, 1987-1990, and Portugal, 1989).

There are 4 classical clinical forms of AHS: pulmonary, cardiac, mixed, and horse sickness fever. The peracute, pulmonary form occurs in fully susceptible animals and has a short course, often only a few hours, and a high mortality rate. The animal exhibits respiratory distress, an extended head and neck, and profuse sweating. Terminally, froth exudes from the nostrils. The cardiac, oedematous form has a more subacute course with mortality reaching 50 percent. The head and neck may show severe swelling that can extend down to the chest. Swelling of the supraorbital fossae is characteristic and may include conjunctival swelling with petechiae. Paralysis of the oesophagus may result in aspiration pneumonia and sublingual haemorrhages are always a poor prognostic sign. The mixed, acute form is most commonly seen and has feature of both the cardiac and pulmonary forms. Horse sickness fever is an often overlooked, mild form of the disease and is seen in resistant equidae such as zebra and donkeys.

The disease has both a seasonal (late summer/autumn) and a cyclical incidence with major epizootics in southern Africa during warm-phase events. Mortality due to AHS is related to the species of equidae affected and to the strain or serotype of the virus. Among equidae, horses are the most susceptible to AHS with a mortality rate of 50-95 percent, followed by mules with mortality around 50 percent. In enzootic regions of Africa, donkeys are very resistant to AHS and experience only subclinical infections. In European and Asian countries, however, donkeys are moderately susceptible and have a mortality rate of 10 percent. Zebras are also markedly resistant with no clinical signs, except fever, and may have extended viraemia (up to 40 days).

For additional background information, including diagnostic methods and references, please refer to the OIE Terrestrial Manual 2013, Chapter 2.5.1. "African horse sickness" at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.05.01_AHS.pdf (adopted by the OIE World Assembly of Delegates, May 2012)

The reader can also refer to Mod.AS's commentaries on African horse sickness published recently in ProMED-mail post archive number 20140303.2311225.

Pictures of post mortem lesions caused by AHS virus can be seen at http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/DiseaseInfo/clinical-signs-photos.php?name=african-horse-sickness.

Maps of South Africa can be seen at http://www.ephotopix.com/south_africa_province_map.html and http://healthmap.org/r/awB6. - Mods.CRD/AS]
